50|$|In the {{election}} of July 6, 1937, citizens voted for change. Popular Bluefield newsman William C. Snyder, of the Bluefield Daily Telegraph, led the ticket of a new city board. As soon as the board could reorganize, Snyder became mayor, and the board appointed Mitchell to serve as city manager. On Sept. 6, 1937, Mitchell was formally sworn in to serve as city manager. He didn’t make any friends when <b>he</b> <b>recommended</b> <b>the</b> installation of a novelty of the time — parking meters — to address the city’s traffic challenges, and he made even fewer friends when <b>he</b> <b>recommended</b> <b>the</b> creation of a Parks & Recreation Commission.|$|R
